{% extends "base.jinja" %}
{% block title %}Course Page{% endblock %}

{% block content %}

<section class="section-info">
    <div class="container">
        <h2>Course Information</h2>
        <p><strong>Instructor:</strong> Professor John Perez</p>
        <p><strong>Schedule:</strong> Mondays and Wednesdays, from 3:00 PM to 5:00 PM</p>
        <p><strong>Mode:</strong> In-person and Online</p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section-description">
    <div class="container">
        <h2>Course Description</h2>
        <p>This Database course is designed to teach students the fundamental concepts of data storage, 
            retrieval, and management. You will learn how to design, implement, and optimize databases, 
            as well as how to use SQL for querying and manipulating data. The course also covers advanced 
            topics such as normalization, indexing, and transaction management.</p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section-topics">
    <div class="container">
        <h2>Topics Covered</h2>
        <ul class="topic-list">
            <li class="topic-item">
                <h3>Introduction to Databases</h3>
                <p>Learn the basics of databases, including types of databases, database models, and their 
                    real-world applications.</p>
            </li>
            <li class="topic-item">
                <h3>SQL Basics</h3>
                <p>Understand the fundamentals of Structured Query Language (SQL), including SELECT, 
                    INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE commands.</p>
            </li>
            <li class="topic-item">
                <h3>Database Design</h3>
                <p>Explore concepts like entity-relationship (ER) modeling, normalization, and creating 
                    efficient database schemas.</p>
            </li>
            <li class="topic-item">
                <h3>Advanced Topics</h3>
                <p>Delve into indexing, stored procedures, triggers, and transaction management to optimize 
                    database performance.</p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</section>

{% endblock %}
